adio National, May 2012; also in Best Australian Science Writing 2013) http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/ockhamsrazor/the-weather-of-who-we-are/4016824;\n\n\u00b7 A Poet's Guide to Climate Change (broadcast on \u201cOckham\u2019s Razor\u201d, Radio National 2012) http://www.abc.net.au/radionational/programs/ockhamsrazor/a-poet27s-guide-to-climate-change/4426198\n\n\u00b7 Getting Over Your Self (Introduction to Sparks, anthology of writing from Uni Sydney creative writing students, 2012) http://www.marktredinnick.com.au/index.php/writing/more/getting_over_your_self/\n\n\u00b7 Prize Life; Praise Life (Introduction to Award-Winning Australian Writing 2012) http://www.marktredinnick.com.au/index.php/writing/more/prize_life_praise_life/\n\n=== As editor ===\n\n* ''A Place on Earth'' (UNSW / U Nebraska, 2003/4)\n* ''Australian Love Poems 2013'' (Inkerman and Blunt, 2013)\n\n=== Prose ===\n\n* ''The Land's Wild Music'' (Trinity, 2005)\n* ''The Blue Plateau: A Landscape Memoir'' (UNSW / Milkweed, 2009)\n* ''Australia's Wild Weather'' (NLA, November 2009)\nFor a full list, see http://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/A14240?mainTabTemplate=agentWorksBy\n\n=== Non-fiction ===\n\n* ''The Little Red Writing Book'' (UNSW, 2006)\n* ''The Little Green Grammar Book'' (UNSW, 2008)\n* ''Writing Well: The Essential Guide'' (Cambridge, 2008)\n* ''The Little Black Book of Business Writing'' with Geoff Whyte (UNSW, 2010)\n\n===Critical studies and reviews of Tredinnick's work ===\n;Fire diary\n* {{cite journal |author=Ryan, Brendan |authorlink=Brendan Ryan (poet) |date=September 2011 |title=Walking the line |journal=Australian Book Review |issue=334 |pages=64}}\n\n\n\n'''Tredinnick Quotables'''\n\n'''Poetry'''\n\n\"Poetry can be maddening; poets, even more so. In particular, one's self. But poetry, as Basho said, is a Way, not an art, or not merely an art. If it's like that for a writer, as it is for Judith Beveridge\u2014as it was for Rumi and was for Heaney and is for me, I think, then there's no quitting it. Unless it quits you.\"\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cPoetry recasts life\u2019s exquisite spell.\u201d \u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cLyric poetry, that deeper speaking, consoles like no other human accomplishment.\u201d \u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cA poem puts your pain and delight back among \u2018the family of things.\u2019 For a poem uses language connected to ecosystems of being and meaning and form and sense where one can feel whole, where one\u2019s sorrow has context, where one\u2019s solitude has company. And not merely social.\u201d \u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\nFrom the intro to ''A Gathered Distance''. \n\n\u201cPoetry reconciles two aspects of mind that are otherwise sundered in most of our waking lives: the making of sense and the making of music, the rational and the spiritual. Poetry reconciles two severed aspects of ourselves.\u201d \u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cMost of a poem, like love, is silence and rhythm.\u201d\n\n\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cIf what poetry is chiefly for is helping restore to unravelling selves their integrity, and if one is a writer, one had better know a little of the self.\u201d\n\n\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\"It's the irrelevant things that take us down into our deepest, truest selves. We need, more than we know, for poetry to be made.\"\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cEach tongue, it has been wisely said, speaks galaxies.\n\nAnd when a language dies, a world\u2014and all that has\n\nNo other being elsewhere\u2014fails; a silence falls\n\nWhere there was song, where there was something known no other\n\nLyric grasps.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick from Litany: An Elegy\n\n\n\u201cUntil later, Bach kicked\n\nThe door in and sat with you on the couch,\n\nAnd you knew you\u2019d never spend\n\nA better day alive again on Earth.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cPoetry is to literature\u2014the wisdom we learn only there\u2014what love is to life. What fire is to a forest. What the trees say, leaving.\u201d\u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cA lasting poem wounds you forever. And it probably wounds you at once, or as soon as you're ready to bear it. And so with love. Poetry is a wound that heals and keeps on healing, saving you from yourself. And reading is all it takes to share its immortal life.\u201d\u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cIn a poem each of us is all of us.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cPoetry, all literature may be a trick humanity evolved to keep us sane.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cLet earth rehearse in us slow words for love. Let love rehearse in earth slow words for time.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cIn the lower branches a rufous fantail turns\n\nAnd demurs, displaying his tail the way a cardsharp\n\nShows his hand\u2014giving nothing but grace away.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cEverything is allowed in a poem, as long as it is well said\u2014in silence and rhythm and image and shapely sound and form. Can a poem break the Fourth Wall and speak to its reader of poetry, of the making of this very poem? The Fourth Wall is apt in fiction and it comes from theatre; poetry is neither of those forms (though it can be, if it chooses to be). The rules of the lyric are both more generous (you can go anywhere you like) and more exacting (only if each phrase aspires to the condition of the song). I have a new collection coming, The Beginner's Guide, which includes a lot of poems on poetry, on making. But where I speak of the poem, the poem may well mean the life. Doubleness (not duplicity, but multiplicity) is poetry's work.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cI have not a muse, but an anti muse, who tells me that everything is wrong.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cRhythm is the real god of poetry.\"\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\"A poem is a window, it gives you the view and the viewer at once and the dance; but the poem is also the glass, it orchestrates a relationship.\"\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cPoetry is what happens when we ask more of language.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cThe work of grief\u2019s the hardest work we get/ To do. It is ten thousand miles to go\u2026 Hope\u2019s the only harder/ Work I know. The stars in sorrow\u2019s sky.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick from \u201cGrief\u2019s Work\u201d\n\n\n\u201cA poem is an architecture of utterance\u2014an act of speech become a nest or a pot. What a poem is, is not just what it says or how it sounds, but also how it looks\u2014its form. Most of a poem's poetry is how a poet's language, like an organism, adapts to where it finds itself\u2014to how it improvises in response to how it is constrained by its form.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick from \"The Gospel of Mark: What I Believe and How I Work\"\n\n\n\"Poems\u2014such small things, like birds and bombs\u2014are a lot bigger than they look; they go off! They make more noise (not to mention mess and other kinds of useful damage) and they travel farther than seems possible. A poem is much larger and wilder, if it\u2019s any good, on the inside than the outside. A poem dances down the cage that keeps it\u2014the cage (the poem\u2019s form) that its making has depended on. What you see is the cage; what you get is the poem escaping it.\"\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnickfrom \u201cThe Gospel of Mark: What I Believe and How I Work\" \n\n\n\"I\u2019m generalising, but not, I think, unfairly: poetry tells the big story small; fiction (most fiction) tells a small story big. Robert Bringshurst puts it this way: \u201cthought is a thread, and the raconteur is the spinner of yarns\u2014but the true storyteller, the poet, is a weaver.\u201d Textus, from which we get \u201ctext\u201d, means (or meant) \u201ccloth\u201d. The poem is a cloth, then; a textus, woven with pieces of a hundred threads (thoughts and stories and hypotheses and epigrams), amounting, at once, to less than any of them, and more than all of them. Leaving nearly all of what it says unsaid.\"\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick from \u201cThe Gospel of Mark: What I Believe and How I Work\" \n\n\n\"A poem is a leaf that tells a book; a page that tells a library. A poem is a hint that nails a thesis to a door.\"\n\n\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick from \u201cThe Gospel of Mark: What I Believe and How I Work\"  \n\n'''Writing'''\n\n\u201cWriting well, like living well, is partly a matter of technique and partly a matter of courage.\u201d\u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cWriting is talking tidied by art and set down on paper.\u201d ''The Little Red Writing Book''\n\n\n\u201cDon't identify as a writer, I might have added; identify with writing.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\u201cWhat makes writing worth writing\u2013\u2013and reading\u2013\u2013is what the story or the poem achieves beyond the tale it tells; its music, its wisdom, its form, the way it makes the ordinary world strangely beautiful.\u201d \u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cWrite one\u2019s self as an instance of all being.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cThe kind of writing that makes most difference identifies with humanity, with all beings, in their beauty and in their need and in their contradictions.\u201d\u2014Mark Tredinnick \n\n\n\u201cThe writer is a partisan of the broken.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cLiterature forgives us for being human.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cThe struggle to improve our sentences is the struggle to improve ourselves.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick from ''The Little Red Writing Book'' \n\n\u201cWrite with your days the lines/ That run between the stars.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick from \u201cWhat the Light Tells\u201d\n\n\n\"Turns out that the art of getting out of your own way, so that you sound on paper like your own true self, is hard work, and it\u2019s achieved by mastering of a bunch of disciplines. As in yoga or meditation, the purpose of the rules is not mastery of the rules. The purpose is to free yourself and your writing \u2013 from distraction and chatter and banality and superficiality. What you can teach, what no writer can do without learning, are the technical matters that have their equivalent in other human arts and sports and pursuits: sentence craft, the things White and Hemingway and Kenyon taught me; grammar and punctuation; the ageless elements of style; and in poetry several thousand years of wisdom about prosody and form, metaphor and meter, sense and sensibility and the music of speech.\"\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n'''Belonging''' \n\n\u201cThere is a practice of belonging, and it begins with forgetfulness of self.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick from ''The Blue Plateau''\n\n\n\u201cI am made of pieces and of the spaces between them where other pieces used to be and no longer are.\u201d \u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick from ''The Blue Plateau'' \n\n\u201cI am a landscape of loss. Most of me is the memory of where else, and who else, and with whom, I have been and no longer am. And so it is with the Plateau; she too, is a landscape of loss. We are not\u2013\u2013not I nor this place\u2013\u2013ever whole; we are never of a piece. Who we are is how what\u2019s left of us falls back toward some kind of coherence much older than we are.\u201d \u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick from ''The Blue Plateau''\n\n\n\u201cHome is not always where you start from; home is where you arrive. Home is the country that, whenever and wherever you find it, won\u2019t leave you. Perhaps it is many such places, an impossible tectonic collage.\"\n\n\u2013\u2013 Mark Tredinnick.\n\n\n\u201cTo live is to move among the lives of others.\u201d\u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cDespair like Job\u2019s may be understood, whatever causes it, as a falling out of wonder with the world, out of awe, a catastrophic failure of conviction about one\u2019s own miraculous part in the larger scheme of things. Life loses shape and refuses form; the hearth that held you lets you slip. One is unhoused from one\u2019s days and tortured by one\u2019s nights. One is beyond one\u2019s own or anyone\u2019s reach. My version of Job\u2019s lot has felt like profound disenchantment with myself and my work. Even the world of birds and ridgetops and rivers and trees lost its magic. Each morning I wake and my life is something less than a theoretical proposition. My unhearthing is a spiritual distemper; it is a loss of one\u2019s grip on the meaning of a life, a nihilism to which, perhaps, those of us most dedicated to the making of meaning are most vulnerable. And it falls especially hard on those who never learned how to care for themselves, who never, early, learned to feel what they said they knew\u2014that the nature of the universe is love, and that some of that love is meant for oneself, a birthright, and secure.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick 2018, \u201cTemple of the Word\u201d \n\n\n\u201cLived as a place, not just a story, lived as country, perhaps a life may become more habitable and happy. Perhaps a place is a mind one can learn to share. Perhaps a place is a body one can inhabit and care for as if it were one\u2019s family, one\u2019s lover. One\u2019s self.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick 2018, \u201cNourishing Terrains\u201d\n\n\n\u201cThe weather is how the sky behaves when it turns up at your place.\u201d\u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\u201cFire is wise, if indiscriminate. It's my hope we humans, especially we colonisers, find some deeper \u2018wisdom in the firegrounds.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\u201cWe carry our countries into the world with us and through it and sometimes out again.\u201d \u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\u201cPerhaps a place is a mind you can learn to share.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick from \u201cNourishing Terrains\u201d \n\n'''Soul''' \n\n\u201c\u2026and all there is is all the love one\u2019s life is worthy of.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cLove is the forest and love is the fire that burns the forest to the ground.\u201d\u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cDarkness is the original country, and it is alive with stories.\"\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick from Bluewren Cantos \n\n\n\u201cLet love be the Pan in your pandemic.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cDeeper than identity is the self.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cI don\u2019t wish to speak against identity; it has its many advocates. I wish to speak a word for self.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cMost of who one is, I want to say, cannot be explained, or contained, or in any sense captured by a cause, or a gender, an ideology, or a theory or a tribal affiliation. There is something irreducible in each of us \u2014 and in our being, each of us, unique, we are the same. Each a unique instance of the human. Deeper than identity is the self.\u201d\u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cDeeper than identity is the Self.\u201d \u201cI am Nobody? Are you Nobody, too?\u201d\u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cEach of us is all of us in a poem. A great poem expresses all our Selves.\u201d\u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cPoetry is for soul making, Keats thought. And he was right. He still is. It still is. How you write is who you are, says Joan Didion. So, who are we and who do we want to be? Poetry's a way to work that out. Each of us. All of us.\"\u2014Mark Tredinnick, Meanjin interview, 2014\n\n\n\"If I weren\u2019t a writer I\u2019d be leading somebody else\u2019s life.\"\u2014Mark Tredinnick \n\n'''Philosophy''' \n\n\u201cAnd the truth lies, all the time, (somewhere) between the shadow and the flower.\u201d\u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cAnd with each dialect drowned, each lexicon beached, the world that is a universe of all these knowing realms knows less, the living world grows less alive.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick from \u201cLitany: An Elegy\u201d \n\n\n\u201cNo matter what others call us, we are what we are. One person\u2019s occident is the other\u2019s orient.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cLet your life\u2014such as it is\u2014do justice to the gift your life is. Make each step a ritual of resistance, each breath an act of kindness.\u201d\u2014Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cI\u2019m just a small metaphor for the world hereabouts.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\"We are a society that is addicted to happiness and speed and light.\"\u2013\u2013 Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cRhythm is the body\u2019s truth.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cOur futures depend on how well we care for the health of our languages and the health of our places.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cMost of it is black, and the beginning goes on/ And on.\u201d\u2013\u2013 Mark Tredinnick from \u201cWhat the Light Tells\u201d\n\n\n\u201cI have a general theory: keep going.\u201d\u2013\u2013 Mark Tredinnick from \u201cThe Rules for Walking\u201d \n\n\n'''Politics''' \n\n\u201cIt\u2019s frightening to contemplate the havoc already at play and terrifying to think about how much worse it could all get and not merely for oneself. If one\u2019s ethics extend beyond one\u2019s self and even beyond the merely human realm, it\u2019s chastening, it\u2019s mortifying, to think that how you have lived your life, how you\u2019ve fuelled your prosperity and ease, has induced a change in the weather the consequence of which could be, already is, massive species extinction including ultimately perhaps our own. \n\n\nWe are already living through the sixth mass extinction event we know about in the history of the earth. Much of it is caused by how immoderately we have thrown our weight around, how many habitats we\u2019ve rendered unliveable, how many food chains we\u2019ve cut; but some of it also and most of it in the years ahead will be caused by the changing weather, much of which we seem to have caused too.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick 2012, \u201cA Poet's Guide to Climate Change\u201d \n\n\n\u201cWE THE colonisers have put up a suburb in a fireground, in a landscape fashioned by fire and prone to it; and in all it\u2019s taken to clear the land to accommodate our suburban idyll, we\u2019ve denied the nature of the place. And by reason of all we\u2019ve cleared and all we\u2019ve fabricated and so artfully manufactured\u2014and by reason of all the former worlds we\u2019ve burned to keep ourselves warmer, or cooler, than the place wanted to be, to move faster than it wanted to move\u2014we\u2019ve made this land more apt to burn, taking down with it our ill-chosen metaphor and the lives we\u2019ve made, thinking them safe, in its rooms; imperilling the lives of all the beings who had accommodated themselves more eloquently to where they were, at home\u2014if not always at ease\u2014in a continent of fire.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cFor that is how it was, this fire country, improved by how its first people lived here, when the West found it and began to make it over into a suburb.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cHere we stand, on the leading edge of a climate catastrophe, still hoping, against all the ashen evidence, it's a suburb.\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\"Contemn the weather long enough, and this is what you'll earn: the light, a sallow holiness of grief...\"\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n\n\u201cEvery climate crisis starts at home.\u201d \u201cThe Fire & the River & the City & the Bush\u201d\u2013\u2013Mark Tredinnick\n\n<br />\n== References ==\n# http://montrealprize.com/about-us/2011-competition/2011-montreal-prize-winner/\n# [https://web.archive.org/web/20140429044726/http://www.literaturewales.org/cipc/i/141520/ Cardiff International Poetry Competition 2012 \u2013 The Winners]. \n# [http://pba.slwa.wa.gov.au/awards_archive/2010 Western Australian Premier's Book Awards \u2013 2010].\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.marktredinnick.com.au}}\n* [http://www.poetryarchive.org/poetryarchive/singlePoet.do?poetId=12219 Profile at the Poetry Archive]\n* [http://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/books/poet-walks-away-with-major-international-prize-20111218-1p0lr.html Profile at the Sydney Morning Herald]\n\n<!-- Just press the \"Save page\" button below without changing anything! Doing so will submit your article submission for review. Once you have saved this page you will find a new yellow 'Review waiting' box at the bottom of your submission page. If you have submitted your page previously, either the old pink 'Submission declined' template or the old grey 'Draft' template will still appear at the top of your submission page, but you should ignore it. Again, please don't change anything in this text box. Just press the \"Save page\" button below. -->\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tredinnick, Mark}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian poets]]\n[[Category:Australian essayists]]\n[[Category:Male essayists]]\n[[Category:Meanjin people]]\n[[Category:Australian male poets]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Medal of the Order of Australia]]\n", "name_user": "Momentary Memoir", "label": "safe", "comment": "FORMAT", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Tredinnick"}
{"title_page": "Heherson Alvarez", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| honorific_suffix    = \n| name                = Heherson T. Alvarez\n| image               = \n| order               = \n| office              = [[Department of the Environment and Natural Resources|Secretary of the Environment and Natural Resources]]\n| President           = [[Gloria Macapagal Arroyo]]\n| term_start          = March 29, 2001\n| term_end            = December 13, 2002\n| predecessor         = [[Antonio Cerilles]]\n| successor           = Elisea G. Gozun\n| office2              = Member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]] from [[Isabela (province)|Isabela]]'s [[Legislative districts of Isabela#4th District|Fourth District]]\n| term_start2          = June 30, 1998\n| term_end2            = June 30, 2001\n| predecessor2         = Antonio M. Abaya\n| successor2           = Antonio M. Abaya\n| office3             = [[Senator of the Philippines]]\n| term_start3         = June 30, 1987\n| term_end3           = June 30, 1998\n| office4             = [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform]]\n| President           = [[Corazon Aquino]]\n| term_start4         = February 7, 1987\n| term_end4           = March 7, 1987\n| predecessor4        = ''Post Created''\n| successor4          = Vacant<ref>vacant after his resignation</ref><small>Post later held by Philip E. Juico</Small>\n| office5             = [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Minister of Agrarian Reform]]\n| president5          = [[Corazon Aquino]]\n| term_start5         = May 1, 1986\n| term_end5           = February 7, 1987\n| predecessor5        = [[Conrado F. Estrella]]\n| successor5          = ''Post Abolished''\n| birth_name          = Heherson Turingan Alvarez\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1939|10|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Santiago, Isabela]], [[Commonwealth of the Philippines]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2020|4|20|1939|10|16|df=y}}\n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = [[Philippines|Filipino]]\n| party               = [[Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino|LDP]](1988-1998);(2004\u2013present), [[Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino|LDP]]-[[Agapito Aquino|Aquino]] Wing(2004)\n| otherparty          = [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP-Laban]](1986-1988), [[Lakas\u2013CMD (1991)|Lakas NUCD-UMDP]](1998-2001)\n| spouse              = Cecile Guidote\n| relations           = sibilings: Rico, Marsman, Manuelito, Reward, Daisy, Pet\n| children            = 2, Hexilon and Xilca\n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = [[Harvard University]], [[University of the Philippines]]\n| occupation          = \n| profession          = [[Politician]]\n| religion            = [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]\n| signature           = \n| website             = http://www.hehersonalvarez.com/\n}}\n\n'''Heherson \"Sonny\" Turingan Alvarez''' (October 16, 1939 \u2013 April 20, 2020) was a politician from the Philippines. He served as a member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines]] and the [[Senate of the Philippines]]. He also was [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform]], and [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Minister of Agrarian Reform]].\n\n==Education==\nSonny Alvarez studied liberal arts at University of the Philippines. He also earned a master's degree in Economics and Public Administration from [[Harvard University]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAlvarez married Cecile Guidote; the couple had two children, Hexilon and Xilca.\n\nOn April 20th, 2020, Alvarez died of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/31/Sonny-Cecile-Alvarez-COVID-19.html|title=Former Senator Sonny Alvarez, wife Cecile Guidote in critical condition due to COVID-19|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{navboxes\n|title=Senatorial history of Heherson Alvarez\n|list=\n{{8th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{9th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{10th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alvarez, Heherson}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Filipino environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino politicians]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 10th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 9th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 8th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Representatives of the Philippines from Isabela (province)]]\n[[Category:People from Santiago (Philippine city)]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of Agrarian Reform of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of Environment and Natural Resources of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:Filipino expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Corazon Aquino Administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:University of the Philippines alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable]]\n| honorific_suffix    = \n| name                = Heherson T. Alvarez\n| image               = \n| order               = \n| office              = Member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]] from [[Isabela (province)|Isabela]]'s [[Legislative districts of Isabela#4th District|Fourth District]]\n| term_start          = June 30, 1998\n| term_end            = June 30, 2001\n| predecessor         = Antonio M. Abaya\n| successor           = Antonio M. Abaya\n| office2             = [[Senator of the Philippines]]\n| term_start2         = June 30, 1987\n| term_end2           = June 30, 1998\n| office3             = [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform]]\n| President           = [[Corazon Aquino]]\n| term_start3         = February 7, 1987\n| term_end3           = March 7, 1987\n| predecessor3        = ''Post Created''\n| successor3          = Vacant<ref>vacant after his resignation</ref><small>Post later held by Philip E. Juico</Small>\n| office4             = [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Minister of Agrarian Reform]]\n| president4          = [[Corazon Aquino]]\n| term_start4         = May 1, 1986\n| term_end4           = February 7, 1987\n| predecessor4        = [[Conrado F. Estrella]]\n| successor4          = ''Post Abolished''\n| birth_name          = Heherson Turingan Alvarez\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1939|10|16|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Santiago, Isabela]], [[Commonwealth of the Philippines]]\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2020|4|20|1939|10|16|df=y}}\n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = [[Philippines|Filipino]]\n| party               = [[Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino|LDP]](1988-1998);(2004\u2013present), [[Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino|LDP]]-[[Agapito Aquino|Aquino]] Wing(2004)\n| otherparty          = [[Partido Demokratiko Pilipino-Lakas ng Bayan|PDP-Laban]](1986-1988), [[Lakas\u2013CMD (1991)|Lakas NUCD-UMDP]](1998-2001)\n| spouse              = Cecile Guidote\n| relations           = sibilings: Rico, Marsman, Manuelito, Reward, Daisy, Pet\n| children            = 2, Hexilon and Xilca\n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = [[Harvard University]], [[University of the Philippines]]\n| occupation          = \n| profession          = [[Politician]]\n| religion            = [[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]]\n| signature           = \n| website             = http://www.hehersonalvarez.com/\n}}\n\n'''Heherson \"Sonny\" Turingan Alvarez''' (October 16, 1939 \u2013 April 20, 2020) was a politician from the Philippines. He served as a member of the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines]] and the [[Senate of the Philippines]]. He also was [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform]], and [[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Minister of Agrarian Reform]].\n\n==Education==\nSonny Alvarez studied liberal arts at University of the Philippines. He also earned a master's degree in Economics and Public Administration from [[Harvard University]].\n\n==Personal life==\nAlvarez married Cecile Guidote; the couple had two children, Hexilon and Xilca.\n\nOn April 20th, 2020, Alvarez died of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/31/Sonny-Cecile-Alvarez-COVID-19.html|title=Former Senator Sonny Alvarez, wife Cecile Guidote in critical condition due to COVID-19|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{navboxes\n|title=Senatorial history of Heherson Alvarez\n|list=\n{{8th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{9th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n{{10th Congress of the Philippines senators}}\n}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alvarez, Heherson}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Filipino environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Laban ng Demokratikong Pilipino politicians]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 10th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 9th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Senators of the 8th Congress of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Representatives of the Philippines from Isabela (province)]]\n[[Category:People from Santiago (Philippine city)]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of Agrarian Reform of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of Environment and Natural Resources of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government alumni]]\n[[Category:Filipino expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Corazon Aquino Administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:University of the Philippines alumni]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines]]\n", "name_user": "June121898", "label": "safe", "comment": "Update to bio", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heherson_Alvarez"}
{"title_page": "Midrasha", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=January 2008}}\nA '''''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''''' ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]: {{hebrew|\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9\u05d4}}, pl. ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot/midrashas}}'') refers to an institute of [[Torah study|Jewish studies]] for women. In [[Israel]], it is often an [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] institution that caters solely to women, and roughly the equivalent of a [[yeshiva]] for men. The term is often translated as '[[seminary]]'.{{fact|date=October 2014}} \n\nIn [[Israel]], a midrasha that offers [[academic degree|degree studies]] is sometimes called a ''machon'' (institute). Some ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}''  accept both men and women, such as the Ein Prat Midrasha<ref>[http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html Eni Prat Midrasha Bogrim.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071101012427/http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html |date=2007-11-01 }}</ref> in Israel.\n\nIn the [[United States]], the term has also been used to refer to co-educational Jewish studies programs, allowing high school students to continue their Jewish education post [[bar mitzvah|bar]] / [[bat mitzvah]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word \"''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''\" is based on the term ''[[beit midrash]]'', \"house of study\".  It is [[cognate]] with the [[Arabic]] \"''{{transl|ar|[[madrasa|madrasah]]}}'',\" which also refers to a place of learning.\n\n==Structure==\n''{{lang|he-Latn|Midrashot}}'' vary in curriculum and [[Orthodox Judaism#Social and philosophic differences|philosophy]]. \nAll cover [[Tanakh|Hebrew Bible]], [[Jewish philosophy]], [[Halacha|Jewish law]]  and [[Musar Literature|Ethics (Musar)]] / [[Hasidic philosophy]]. See [[Yeshiva #Curriculum]]. The weight and role assigned to Talmud will differ.\nMore liberal ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' place more emphasis on the study of [[Talmud]] itself, as in men's {{lang|he-Latn|[[yeshiva|yeshivot]]}};\n(Institutions here include [[Matan_Women's_Institute_for_Torah_Studies|Matan]], [[Nishmat (midrasha)|Nishmat]] and [[Midreshet Lindenbaum]].)\nMore conservative ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' incorporate selections from the Talmud, but only in the context of other classes - particular philosophy and Musar. Most ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' in this latter category are [[Haredi]] aligned, and are modeled on the [[Beis Yaakov]] teacher-training seminary established by [[Sarah Schenirer]] (for example [[Beth Jacob Jerusalem]]).\nThis includes [[Hassidic]]-aligned institutions (for example [[Beth Rivkah]]).\n\nMany Israeli women study at a Midrasha, post high school - examples are [[Ein_HaNetziv#Education|Ein HaNatziv Women's Seminary]] and [[Migdal Oz (seminary)|Migdal Oz]].\nOften studies continue at one of the religious affiliated [[List_of_universities_and_colleges_in_Israel#Colleges|teacher training colleges]], which offer a religious studies program in conjunction with the [[B.Ed.]] degree. \nOthers such as [[Machon Tal]], associated with the [[Jerusalem College of Technology]], similarly offer degrees in engineering or management.\nSeveral Haredi and Hasidic institutions likewise offer certificates, and sometimes degrees, in Education.\n\nMany diaspora-based Orthodox Jewish girls attend a ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}'' in Israel for a year or more following high school. \nSome ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' are designed for [[baal teshuva|the newly observant]] (see for example [[Neve Yerushalayim]], [[Machon Roni]]).\nMost ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' for English-speaking students are accredited by American colleges. Some ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' offer second-year programs with religious-studies classes in the morning and general-studies classes in the afternoons, allowing students to pursue a religious education and a general-studies education leading to a college degree simultaneously. \n<!-- \n==Coed high school Midrashot==\nWhile a [[Hebrew school]] program typically handles [[Jewish education]] for youths before their [[Bar/Bat Mitzvah]], students who wish to continue their Jewish education through high school enroll in a Midrasha.\n -->\n\n==See also==\n* [[Beis Yaakov]]\n* [[List of Midrashot]]\n* [[Role of women in Judaism]]\n* [[Female seminary]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Jewish education}}\n\n<!-- Categories -->\n[[Category:Jewish educational institutions]]\n[[Category:Modern Orthodox Judaism]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish schools for women]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=January 2008}}\nA '''''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''''' ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]: {{hebrew|\u05de\u05d3\u05e8\u05e9\u05d4}}, pl. ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot/midrashas}}'') refers to an institute of [[Torah study|Jewish studies]] for women. In [[Israel]], it is often an [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox]] institution that caters solely to women, and roughly the equivalent of a [[yeshiva]] for men. The term is often translated as '[[seminary]]'.{{fact|date=October 2014}} \n\nIn [[Israel]], a midrasha that offers [[academic degree|degree studies]] is sometimes called a ''machon'' (institute). Some ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}''  accept both men and women, such as the Ein Prat Midrasha<ref>[http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html Eni Prat Midrasha Bogrim.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071101012427/http://www.bogrim.org/en_index.html |date=2007-11-01 }}</ref> in Israel.\n\nIn the [[United States]], the term has also been used to refer to co-educational Jewish studies programs, allowing high school students to continue their Jewish education post [[bar mitzvah|bar]] / [[bat mitzvah]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Etymology==\nThe word \"''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}''\" is based on the term ''[[beit midrash]]'', \"house of study\".  It is [[cognate]] with the [[Arabic]] \"''{{transl|ar|[[madrasa|madrasah]]}}'',\" which also refers to a place of learning.\n\n==Structure==\n''{{lang|he-Latn|Midrashot}}'' vary in curriculum and [[Orthodox Judaism#Social and philosophic differences|philosophy]]. \nAll cover [[Tanakh|Hebrew Bible]], [[Jewish philosophy]], [[Halacha|Jewish law]]  and [[Musar Literature|Ethics (Musar)]] / [[Hasidic philosophy]]. See [[Yeshiva #Curriculum]]. The weight and role assigned to Talmud will differ.\nMore liberal ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' place more emphasis on the study of [[Talmud]] itself, as in men's {{lang|he-Latn|[[yeshiva|yeshivot]]}};\n(Institutions here include [[Matan_Women's_Institute_for_Torah_Studies|Matan]], [[Nishmat (midrasha)|Nishmat]] and [[Midreshet Lindenbaum]].)\nMore conservative ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' incorporate selections from the Talmud, but only in the context of other classes - particular philosophy and Musar. Most ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' in this latter category are [[Haredi]] aligned, and are modeled on the [[Beis Yaakov]] teacher-training seminary established by [[Sarah Schenirer]] (for example [[Beth Jacob Jerusalem]]).\nThis includes [[Hassidic]]-aligned institutions (for example [[Beth Rivkah]]).\n\nMany Israeli women study at a Midrasha, post high school - examples are [[Ein_HaNetziv#Education|Ein HaNatziv Women's Seminary]] and [[Migdal Oz (seminary)|Migdal Oz]].\nOften studies continue at one of the religious affiliated [[List_of_universities_and_colleges_in_Israel#Colleges|teacher training colleges]], which offer a religious studies program in conjunction with the [[B.Ed.]] degree. \nOthers such as [[Machon Tal]], associated with the [[Jerusalem College of Technology]], similarly offer degrees in engineering or management.\nSeveral Haredi and Hasidic institutions offer certificates, and sometimes degrees, in Education.\n\nMany diaspora-based Orthodox Jewish girls attend a ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrasha}}'' in Israel for a year or more following high school. \nSome ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' are designed for [[baal teshuva|the newly observant]] (see for example [[Neve Yerushalayim]], [[Machon Roni]]).\nMost ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' for English-speaking students are accredited by American colleges. Some ''{{lang|he-Latn|midrashot}}'' offer second-year programs with religious-studies classes in the morning and general-studies classes in the afternoons, allowing students to pursue a religious education and a general-studies education leading to a college degree simultaneously. \n<!-- \n==Coed high school Midrashot==\nWhile a [[Hebrew school]] program typically handles [[Jewish education]] for youths before their [[Bar/Bat Mitzvah]], students who wish to continue their Jewish education through high school enroll in a Midrasha.\n -->\n\n==See also==\n* [[Beis Yaakov]]\n* [[List of Midrashot]]\n* [[Role of women in Judaism]]\n* [[Female seminary]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Jewish education}}\n\n<!-- Categories -->\n[[Category:Jewish educational institutions]]\n[[Category:Modern Orthodox Judaism]]\n[[Category:Orthodox Jewish schools for women]]\n", "name_user": "Fintor", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eStructure", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Midrasha"}
