{"title_page": "In Fabric", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = In Fabric\n| image          = In Fabric poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Strickland (director)|Peter Strickland]]\n| producer       = Andrew Starke\n| writer         = Peter Strickland\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Marianne Jean-Baptiste]]\n* [[Hayley Squires]]\n* [[Leo Bill]]\n* [[Julian Barratt]]\n* [[Steve Oram]]\n* [[Gwendoline Christie]]\n* [[Barry Adamson]]\n* Jaygann Ayeh\n* [[Richard Bremmer]]\n* Terry Bird\n* Fatma Mohamed\n}}\n| music          = Cavern of Anti-Matter\n| cinematography = Ari Wegner\n| editing        = Matyas Fekete\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* Rook Films\n* [[BBC Films]]\n* [[British Film Institute]]\n* Headgear Films\n* Metrol Technology\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Curzon Artificial Eye]] (United Kingdom) <br> [[A24 (company)|A24]] (United States)\n| released       = 18 September 2018 ([[Toronto International Film Festival|Toronto]]) <br> 28 June 2019 (United Kingdom) <br> 6 December 2019 (United States)\n| runtime        = 118 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''In Fabric''''' is a 2018 British [[horror film|horror]] [[comedy film|comedy]] film, written and directed by [[Peter Strickland (director)|Peter Strickland]]. The film follows a haunted red dress as it torments various owners. It stars [[Marianne Jean-Baptiste]], [[Hayley Squires]], [[Leo Bill]], and [[Gwendoline Christie]]. \n\nIt had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on 13 September 2018. It was released in the United Kingdom on 28 June 2019 by [[Curzon Artificial Eye]] and was released in the United States on 6 December 2019 by [[A24 (company)|A24]].\n\n==Plot==\n\nSheila (Marianne Jean-Baptiste) is a recently divorced bank teller who lives with her son Vince (Jaygann Ayeh). She is frequently chastised for insignificant work errors by her bosses Stash (Julian Barratt) and Clive (Steve Oram), and intimidated by Vince's new girlfriend Gwen (Gwendoline Christie). She visits department store Dentley and Soper's to buy a dress for an upcoming date in the sales. After meeting the enigmatic store clerk Miss Luckmoore (Fatma Mohamed), Sheila is drawn to a beautiful, flowing red dress which she tries on. Luckmoore convinces Sheila to purchase it. \n\nSheila notices a strange rash on her chest after wearing the dress. After putting the dress in the washing machine, the machine breaks down and Sheila injures her hand in the process. Sheila returns to the store to get a new size for the dress only to learn that there is only one version of the dress and that the store model was killed after wearing the dress for the store catalog. Sheila goes on a date with new suitor Zach (Barry Adamson) while Gwen and Vince have sex. As she climaxes, Gwen is almost killed when the dress floats above her and tries to suffocate her.  Sheila and Zach go for a walk together, where Sheila is attacked by an Alsatian, which cuts her leg and rips the dress in the process. Later that day, Vince returns home with the dress which is somehow now fully repaired. After hearing the dress move about in the wardrobe at night, an unsettled Sheila attempts to return the dress to the store but is refused by Luckmoore. Sheila is then killed in a car accident as she is driving en route to spending the night with Zach. \n\nThe dress comes into possession of washing machine repairman Reg Speaks (Leo Bill) who is made by his friends to wear it on a night out. He is engaged to Babs (Hayley Squires), who takes a liking to the dress and decides to wear it as well. Reg returns home and is hypnotised by the department store's TV advertisement while Babs is at the store shopping. Luckmoore is alarmed to see Babs is wearing the dress and demands she leaves. Meanwhile, Reg dies from carbon monoxide poisoning caused by the dress manipulating the boiler. Babs recalls to Luckmoore a dream she had about her being the model for all the dresses in the catalogue but getting thinner and thinner as the dresses got larger and larger. She was then buried in the store by the workers. Babs goes to try on a dress while a fight soon breaks out in the store that quickly spirals into looting. \n\nThe dress catches fire and the flames spread quickly around the store. Babs burns to death, unable to escape her changing room, while Luckmoore flees down into the dumbwaiter with a dismembered mannequin. As she descends deeper into the store, she sees the dead store model, Sheila, Reg, and Babs stitching together the dress from threads made of their blood; they are trapped in eternal servitude. A fireman observes the destroyed store and discovers the dress undamaged amongst the rubble.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Marianne Jean-Baptiste]] as Sheila\n* [[Hayley Squires]] as Babs\n* [[Leo Bill]] as Reg Speaks\n* [[Gwendoline Christie]] as Gwen\n* [[Julian Barratt]] as Stash\n* [[Steve Oram]] as Clive\n* [[Barry Adamson]] as Zach\n* Jaygann Ayeh as Vince\n* [[Richard Bremmer]] as Mr. Lundy\n* Terry Bird as Bananas Brian\n* Fatma Mohamed as Miss Luckmoore\n* [[Sidse Babett Knudsen]] as Jill\n\n==Production==\nIn September 2017, it was announced [[Marianne Jean-Baptiste]] had joined the cast of the film, with [[Peter Strickland (director)|Peter Strickland]] directing from a screenplay he wrote. Andy Starke served as a producer on the film, and Ian Benson, Lizzie Francke, Rose Garnett, Stephen Kelliher, Patrick Howson, Phil Hunt and Compton Ross served as an executive producers on the film under their Blue Bear Rook Films, Bankside Films, [[BBC Films]] and [[British Film Institute]] banners, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/peter-strickland-plots-in-fabric-with-marianne-jean-baptiste-exclusive/5122226.article|title=Peter Strickland plots 'In Fabric' with Marianne Jean-Baptiste (exclusive)|website=[[Screen International]]|first=Tom|last=Grater|date=11 September 2017|accessdate=4 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104211216/https://www.screendaily.com/news/peter-strickland-plots-in-fabric-with-marianne-jean-baptiste-exclusive/5122226.article|archive-date=4 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2017, [[Hayley Squires]], [[Julian Barratt]], [[Gwendoline Christie]], [[Leo Bill]], [[Steve Oram]], Fatma Mohamed, Jaygann Ayeh, and [[Richard Bremmer]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/hayley-squires-julian-barratt-gwendoline-christie-join-peter-stricklands-in-fabric/5124536.article|title=Hayley Squires, Julian Barratt, Gwendoline Christie join Peter Strickland's 'In Fabric'|website=Screen International|first=Sam|last=Warner|date=28 November 2017|accessdate=4 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628044142/https://www.screendaily.com/news/hayley-squires-julian-barratt-gwendoline-christie-join-peter-stricklands-in-fabric/5124536.article|archive-date=28 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStrickland commented that when writing the script he drew inspiration from both the curious nature of [[second-hand shop]]s and his memories of being taken to department stores as a child, in particular the now closed [[Jacksons (department store)|Jacksons]] head branch in [[Reading, Berkshire]]. He wanted to interrogate the reactions people have to clothing. The dress itself was therefore very important. It also needed to fit a range of body types, so costume designer Jo Thompson made a simple red silk [[wrap dress]].<ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite news |last1=Kelley |first1=Sonaiya |title=In Peter Strickland's gleefully demented 'In Fabric,' an upscale department store serves as a shop of horrors |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2019-12-06/in-fabric-peter-strickland-gwendoline-christie-marianne-jean-baptiste |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn March 2018, [[Curzon Artificial Eye]] acquired U.K. distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/peter-stricklands-in-fabric-lands-uk-deal-exclusive/5127488.article|title=Peter Strickland's 'In Fabric' lands UK deal (exclusive)|website=Screen International|first=Tom|last=Grater|date=15 March 2018|accessdate=4 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104211212/https://www.screendaily.com/news/peter-stricklands-in-fabric-lands-uk-deal-exclusive/5127488.article|archive-date=4 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The film had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on 13 September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tiff.net/tiff/in-fabric/|title=In Fabric|website=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=4 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104211112/https://www.tiff.net/tiff/in-fabric/|archive-date=4 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly after, [[A24 (company)|A24]] acquired U.S. distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/in-fabric-sold-a24-1202947075/|title=A24 Buys Horror-Thriller 'In Fabric' for North America|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=18 September 2018|accessdate=4 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213070558/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/in-fabric-sold-a24-1202947075/|archive-date=13 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It was released in the United Kingdom on 28 June 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.launchingfilms.com/release-schedule|title=In Fabric|website=Launching Films|accessdate=April 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405173159/https://www.launchingfilms.com/release-schedule|archive-date=April 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It was released in the United States on 6 December 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://a24films.com/films/in-fabric|title=In Fabric|publisher=[[A24 (company)|A24]]|accessdate=August 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828085549/https://a24films.com/films/in-fabric|archive-date=August 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''In Fabric'' received universal acclaim from film critics. As of November 2019, it held a 94% approval rating on Rotten Tomatoes, based on 137 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads \"''In Fabric''{{'}}s gauzy giallo allure weaves a surreal spell, blending stylish horror and dark comedy to offer audiences a captivating treat.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/in_fabric/|title=In Fabric (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191106191745/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/in_fabric|archive-date=November 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On Metacritic, the film holds a rating of 84 out of 100, based on 25 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metacritic.com/movie/in-fabric|title=In Fabric Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=October 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nUpon its UK release, ''The Independent'' called the film \"''[[Suspiria]]'' set in a department store\" and commented that it was Strickland at \"his most free and playful\".<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite news |last1=Loughrey |first1=Clarisse |title=In Fabric review: It's Suspiria set in a department store |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/in-fabric-review-horror-film-peter-strickland-plot-cast-a8976936.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=27 June 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628152702/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/in-fabric-review-horror-film-peter-strickland-plot-cast-a8976936.html |archive-date=28 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' enjoyed the \"dry, daft wit that reveals itself in surprising ways, from the bonkers premise onwards\".<ref name=\"Empire\">{{cite news |last1=Nugent |first1=John |title=In Fabric |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/reviews/fabric-review/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Empire |date=24 June 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904044420/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/reviews/fabric-review/ |archive-date=4 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Writing in the ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Mark Kermode]] made it his film of the week and praised the \"heady mix of intoxicating nostalgia, clothing-related alchemy and horror-inflected twisted comedy\".<ref name=\"Kermode\">{{cite news |last1=Kermode |first1=Mark |title=In Fabric review \u2013 rides a fine seam between humour and horror |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/jun/30/in-fabric-review-peter-strickland-marianne-jean-baptiste |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=30 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130213746/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/jun/30/in-fabric-review-peter-strickland-marianne-jean-baptiste |archive-date=30 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nInternationally, critics also lauded the film. ''[[The New York Times]]'' stated it was Strickland's \"most impressive, engrossing, imaginatively unchained work yet\".<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |last1=Kenny |first1=Glen |title='In Fabric' Review: The Dress Is Possessed. But It Was on Sale. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/05/movies/in-fabric-review.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=5 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102110632/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/05/movies/in-fabric-review.html |archive-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Rolling Stone]] summed up the film as \"a singular trip into a singularly warped mind\".<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite news |last1=Fear |first1=David |title='In Fabric': Devil in a Red Dress (Literally) |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/in-fabric-movie-review-920448/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=5 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406152857/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/in-fabric-movie-review-920448/ |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''In Fabric'' was included in best of 2019 film lists in ''The Playlist'' and ''[[Sight & Sound]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 25 Best Films Of 2019|url=https://theplaylist.net/25-best-films-2019-20191205/|publisher=The Playlist|access-date=2020-04-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209153319/https://theplaylist.net/25-best-films-2019-20191205/|archive-date=2019-12-09|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The 50 Best Films Of 2019|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/best-films-2019|publisher=British Film Institute|access-date=2020-04-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328234323/https://www.bfi.org.uk/best-films-2019|archive-date=2020-03-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official site|https://a24films.com/films/in-fabric}}\n* {{IMDB title|7464188}}\n* {{Metacritic film|in-fabric}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|m/in_fabric}}\n\n{{Peter Strickland (director)}}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2018 horror films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British horror films]]\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:British supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1983]]\n[[Category:Films set in department stores]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = In Fabric\n| image          = In Fabric poster.jpg\n| alt            = \n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Peter Strickland (director)|Peter Strickland]]\n| producer       = Andrew Starke\n| writer         = Peter Strickland\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Marianne Jean-Baptiste]]\n* [[Hayley Squires]]\n* [[Leo Bill]]\n* [[Julian Barratt]]\n* [[Steve Oram]]\n* [[Gwendoline Christie]]\n* [[Barry Adamson]]\n* Jaygann Ayeh\n* [[Richard Bremmer]]\n* Terry Bird\n* Fatma Mohamed\n}}\n| music          = Cavern of Anti-Matter\n| cinematography = Ari Wegner\n| editing        = Matyas Fekete\n| production companies = {{Plainlist|\n* Rook Films\n* [[BBC Films]]\n* [[British Film Institute]]\n* Headgear Films\n* Metrol Technology\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Curzon Artificial Eye]] (United Kingdom) <br> [[A24 (company)|A24]] (United States)\n| released       = 18 September 2018 ([[Toronto International Film Festival|Toronto]]) <br> 28 June 2019 (United Kingdom) <br> 6 December 2019 (United States)\n| runtime        = 118 minutes\n| country        = United Kingdom\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''In Fabric''''' is a 2018 British [[horror film|horror]] [[comedy film|comedy]] film, written and directed by [[Peter Strickland (director)|Peter Strickland]]. The film follows a haunted red dress as it torments various owners. It stars [[Marianne Jean-Baptiste]], [[Hayley Squires]], [[Leo Bill]], and [[Gwendoline Christie]]. \n\nIt had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on 13 September 2018. It was released in the United Kingdom on 28 June 2019 by [[Curzon Artificial Eye]] and was released in the United States on 6 December 2019 by [[A24 (company)|A24]].\n\n==Plot==\n\nSheila (Marianne Jean-Baptiste) is a recently divorced bank teller who lives with her son Vince (Jaygann Ayeh). She is frequently chastised for insignificant work errors by her bosses Stash (Julian Barratt) and Clive (Steve Oram), and intimidated by Vince's new girlfriend Gwen (Gwendoline Christie). She visits department store Dentley and Soper's to buy a dress for an upcoming date in the sales. After meeting the enigmatic store clerk Miss Luckmoore (Fatma Mohamed), Sheila is drawn to a beautiful, flowing red dress which she tries on. Luckmoore convinces Sheila to purchase it. \n\nSheila notices a strange rash on her chest after wearing the dress. After putting the dress in the washing machine, the machine breaks down and Sheila injures her hand in the process. Sheila returns to the store to get a new size for the dress only to learn that there is only one version of the dress and that the store model was killed after wearing the dress for the store catalog. Sheila goes on a date with new suitor Zach (Barry Adamson) while Gwen and Vince have sex. As she climaxes, Gwen is almost killed when the dress floats above her and tries to suffocate her.  Sheila and Zach go for a walk together, where Sheila is attacked by an Alsatian, which cuts her leg and rips the dress in the process. Later that day, Vince returns home with the dress which is somehow now fully repaired. After hearing the dress move about in the wardrobe at night, an unsettled Sheila attempts to return the dress to the store but is refused by Luckmoore. Sheila is then killed in a car accident as she is driving en route to spending the night with Zach. \n\nThe dress comes into possession of washing machine repairman Reg Speaks (Leo Bill) who is made by his friends to wear it on a night out. He is engaged to Babs (Hayley Squires), who takes a liking to the dress and decides to wear it as well. Reg returns home and is hypnotised by the department store's TV advertisement while Babs is at the store shopping. Luckmoore is alarmed to see Babs is wearing the dress and demands she leaves. Meanwhile, Reg dies from carbon monoxide poisoning caused by the dress manipulating the boiler. Babs recalls to Luckmoore a dream she had about her being the model for all the dresses in the catalogue but getting thinner and thinner as the dresses got larger and larger. She was then buried in the store by the workers. Babs goes to try on a dress while a fight soon breaks out in the store that quickly spirals into looting. \n\nThe dress catches fire and the flames spread quickly around the store. Babs burns to death, unable to escape her changing room, while Luckmoore flees down into the dumbwaiter with a dismembered mannequin. As she descends deeper into the store, she sees the dead store model, Sheila, Reg, and Babs stitching together the dress from threads made of their blood; they are trapped in eternal servitude. A fireman observes the destroyed store and discovers the dress undamaged amongst the rubble.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Marianne Jean-Baptiste]] as Sheila\n* [[Hayley Squires]] as Babs\n* [[Leo Bill]] as Reg Speaks\n* [[Gwendoline Christie]] as Gwen\n* [[Julian Barratt]] as Stash\n* [[Steve Oram]] as Clive\n* [[Barry Adamson]] as Zach\n* Jaygann Ayeh as Vince\n* [[Richard Bremmer]] as Mr. Lundy\n* Terry Bird as Bananas Brian\n* Fatma Mohamed as Miss Luckmoore\n* [[Sidse Babett Knudsen]] as Jill\n\n==Production==\nIn September 2017, it was announced [[Marianne Jean-Baptiste]] had joined the cast of the film, with [[Peter Strickland (director)|Peter Strickland]] directing from a screenplay he wrote. Andy Starke served as a producer on the film, and Ian Benson, Lizzie Francke, Rose Garnett, Stephen Kelliher, Patrick Howson, Phil Hunt and Compton Ross served as an executive producers on the film under their Blue Bear Rook Films, Bankside Films, [[BBC Films]] and [[British Film Institute]] banners, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/peter-strickland-plots-in-fabric-with-marianne-jean-baptiste-exclusive/5122226.article|title=Peter Strickland plots 'In Fabric' with Marianne Jean-Baptiste (exclusive)|website=[[Screen International]]|first=Tom|last=Grater|date=11 September 2017|accessdate=4 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104211216/https://www.screendaily.com/news/peter-strickland-plots-in-fabric-with-marianne-jean-baptiste-exclusive/5122226.article|archive-date=4 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2017, [[Hayley Squires]], [[Julian Barratt]], [[Gwendoline Christie]], [[Leo Bill]], [[Steve Oram]], Fatma Mohamed, Jaygann Ayeh, and [[Richard Bremmer]] joined the cast of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/hayley-squires-julian-barratt-gwendoline-christie-join-peter-stricklands-in-fabric/5124536.article|title=Hayley Squires, Julian Barratt, Gwendoline Christie join Peter Strickland's 'In Fabric'|website=Screen International|first=Sam|last=Warner|date=28 November 2017|accessdate=4 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180628044142/https://www.screendaily.com/news/hayley-squires-julian-barratt-gwendoline-christie-join-peter-stricklands-in-fabric/5124536.article|archive-date=28 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nStrickland commented that when writing the script he drew inspiration from both the curious nature of [[second-hand shops]] and his memories of being taken to department stores as a child, in particular the now closed [[Jacksons (department store)|Jacksons]] head branch in [[Reading, Berkshire]]. He wanted to interrogate the reactions people have to clothing. The dress itself was therefore very important. It also needed to fit a range of body types, so costume designer Jo Thompson made a simple red silk [[wrap dress]].<ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite news |last1=Kelley |first1=Sonaiya |title=In Peter Strickland's gleefully demented 'In Fabric,' an upscale department store serves as a shop of horrors |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/movies/story/2019-12-06/in-fabric-peter-strickland-gwendoline-christie-marianne-jean-baptiste |accessdate=20 April 2020 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nIn March 2018, [[Curzon Artificial Eye]] acquired U.K. distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/peter-stricklands-in-fabric-lands-uk-deal-exclusive/5127488.article|title=Peter Strickland's 'In Fabric' lands UK deal (exclusive)|website=Screen International|first=Tom|last=Grater|date=15 March 2018|accessdate=4 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104211212/https://www.screendaily.com/news/peter-stricklands-in-fabric-lands-uk-deal-exclusive/5127488.article|archive-date=4 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The film had its world premiere at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] on 13 September 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tiff.net/tiff/in-fabric/|title=In Fabric|website=[[Toronto International Film Festival]]|accessdate=4 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181104211112/https://www.tiff.net/tiff/in-fabric/|archive-date=4 November 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly after, [[A24 (company)|A24]] acquired U.S. distribution rights to the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/in-fabric-sold-a24-1202947075/|title=A24 Buys Horror-Thriller 'In Fabric' for North America|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Dave|last=McNary|date=18 September 2018|accessdate=4 November 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181213070558/https://variety.com/2018/film/news/in-fabric-sold-a24-1202947075/|archive-date=13 December 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It was released in the United Kingdom on 28 June 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.launchingfilms.com/release-schedule|title=In Fabric|website=Launching Films|accessdate=April 9, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180405173159/https://www.launchingfilms.com/release-schedule|archive-date=April 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> It was released in the United States on 6 December 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://a24films.com/films/in-fabric|title=In Fabric|publisher=[[A24 (company)|A24]]|accessdate=August 29, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190828085549/https://a24films.com/films/in-fabric|archive-date=August 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''In Fabric'' received universal acclaim from film critics. As of November 2019, it held a 94% approval rating on Rotten Tomatoes, based on 137 reviews. The site's critical consensus reads \"''In Fabric''{{'}}s gauzy giallo allure weaves a surreal spell, blending stylish horror and dark comedy to offer audiences a captivating treat.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/in_fabric/|title=In Fabric (2019)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 7, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191106191745/https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/in_fabric|archive-date=November 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> On Metacritic, the film holds a rating of 84 out of 100, based on 25 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://metacritic.com/movie/in-fabric|title=In Fabric Reviews|website=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=October 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nUpon its UK release, ''The Independent'' called the film \"''[[Suspiria]]'' set in a department store\" and commented that it was Strickland at \"his most free and playful\".<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite news |last1=Loughrey |first1=Clarisse |title=In Fabric review: It's Suspiria set in a department store |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/in-fabric-review-horror-film-peter-strickland-plot-cast-a8976936.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Independent |date=27 June 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190628152702/https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/in-fabric-review-horror-film-peter-strickland-plot-cast-a8976936.html |archive-date=28 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'' enjoyed the \"dry, daft wit that reveals itself in surprising ways, from the bonkers premise onwards\".<ref name=\"Empire\">{{cite news |last1=Nugent |first1=John |title=In Fabric |url=https://www.empireonline.com/movies/reviews/fabric-review/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Empire |date=24 June 2019 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190904044420/https://www.empireonline.com/movies/reviews/fabric-review/ |archive-date=4 September 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Writing in the ''[[The Guardian]]'', [[Mark Kermode]] made it his film of the week and praised the \"heady mix of intoxicating nostalgia, clothing-related alchemy and horror-inflected twisted comedy\".<ref name=\"Kermode\">{{cite news |last1=Kermode |first1=Mark |title=In Fabric review \u2013 rides a fine seam between humour and horror |url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/jun/30/in-fabric-review-peter-strickland-marianne-jean-baptiste |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=30 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191130213746/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2019/jun/30/in-fabric-review-peter-strickland-marianne-jean-baptiste |archive-date=30 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nInternationally, critics also lauded the film. ''[[The New York Times]]'' stated it was Strickland's \"most impressive, engrossing, imaginatively unchained work yet\".<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |last1=Kenny |first1=Glen |title='In Fabric' Review: The Dress Is Possessed. But It Was on Sale. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/05/movies/in-fabric-review.html |accessdate=11 April 2020 |date=5 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102110632/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/12/05/movies/in-fabric-review.html |archive-date=2 January 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Rolling Stone]] summed up the film as \"a singular trip into a singularly warped mind\".<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite news |last1=Fear |first1=David |title='In Fabric': Devil in a Red Dress (Literally) |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/in-fabric-movie-review-920448/ |accessdate=11 April 2020 |work=Rolling Stone |date=5 December 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200406152857/https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/movie-reviews/in-fabric-movie-review-920448/ |archive-date=6 April 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n''In Fabric'' was included in best of 2019 film lists in ''The Playlist'' and ''[[Sight & Sound]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 25 Best Films Of 2019|url=https://theplaylist.net/25-best-films-2019-20191205/|publisher=The Playlist|access-date=2020-04-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191209153319/https://theplaylist.net/25-best-films-2019-20191205/|archive-date=2019-12-09|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The 50 Best Films Of 2019|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/best-films-2019|publisher=British Film Institute|access-date=2020-04-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200328234323/https://www.bfi.org.uk/best-films-2019|archive-date=2020-03-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official site|https://a24films.com/films/in-fabric}}\n* {{IMDB title|7464188}}\n* {{Metacritic film|in-fabric}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|m/in_fabric}}\n\n{{Peter Strickland (director)}}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2018 horror films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British horror films]]\n[[Category:A24 films]]\n[[Category:British supernatural horror films]]\n[[Category:Films about witchcraft]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1983]]\n[[Category:Films set in department stores]]\n[[Category:Films set in England]]\n", "name_user": "Mujinga", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProduction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In_Fabric"}
{"title_page": "2019 Pennsylvania's 12th congressional district special election", "text_new": "{{see also|2019 United States elections}}\n{{short description|Election to fill a U.S. House seat vacated by resignation}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = Pennsylvania's 12th congressional district special election\n| country = Pennsylvania\n| type = by-election\n| ongoing = No\n| previous_election = 2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania#District 12\n| previous_year = 2018\n| election_date = May 21, 2019\n| next_election = 2020 United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania#District 12\n| next_year = 2020\n| seats_for_election = [[Pennsylvania's 12th congressional district]]\n| image1 = [[File:Fred Keller, official portrait, 116th Congress (cropped2).jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee1 = [[Fred Keller (politician)|'''Fred Keller''']]\n| party1 = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1 = '''90,000'''\n| percentage1 = '''68.08%'''\n| map_image = File:2019 Pennsylvania's 12th congressional district special election - Results by county.svg\n| map_size = 270px\n| map_caption = \n| image2 = [[File:No image.svg|x120px]]\n| nominee2 = Marc Friedenberg\n| party2 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2 = 42,195\n| percentage2 = 31.92%\n| title = U.S. Representative\n| before_election = [[Tom Marino]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[Fred Keller (politician)|Fred Keller]]\n| after_party = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Elections in Pennsylvania}}\nA [[special election]] was held on May 21, 2019, to fill the remainder of the term for {{ushr|PA|12}} in the [[United States House of Representatives]] for the [[116th United States Congress]]. [[Tom Marino]], a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], resigned from office effective January 23.\n\n== Background ==\nAs a result of the [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania|2018 elections]], [[United States congressional delegations from Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania's House delegation]] to the [[116th United States Congress|116th U.S. Congress]] took office in early January 2019 with a tie of 9 [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] and 9 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Levy |first=Marc |title=Democrats, 4 of them women, win House seats in Pennsylvania |url=https://www.apnews.com/058759f2b3c548d7884299fbbf357bf7 |agency=Associated Press |date=November 6, 2018 |accessdate=February 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRepublican [[Tom Marino]], the [[incumbent]] representative for {{ushr|PA|12}}, announced his resignation effective January 23, 2019. By state law, [[Governor of Pennsylvania|Governor]] [[Tom Wolf]] was required to call for a special election at least 60 days after the seat became vacant.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Caitlin|last1=Oprysko|first2=Zach|last2=Motellaro |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/01/17/tom-marino-retire-1109470 |title=Pennsylvania GOP Rep. Tom Marino to retire this month |publisher=Politico |date=January 17, 2019 |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> Wolf set the election for May 21.<ref>{{cite tweet|author=[[Tom Wolf]]|user=GovernorTomWolf|number=1088421289008738304|date=January 24, 2019|title=Having heard the concerns of county officials, I am scheduling the special election to fill the remainder of Congressman Marino\u2019s term on May 21, 2019 to coincide with the primary election.|accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> Primary elections were not held in the race. Instead, nominees were chosen by each party.<ref>{{cite web|last=Paez |first=Sarah |url=https://www.centredaily.com/news/local/article224682630.html |title=Congressman Tom Marino resigns, leaving vacancy in Pa.\u2019s 12th district &#124; Centre Daily Times |publisher=Centredaily.com |date= |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> Republicans selected their nominee on March 2.<ref name=\"CVlist\"/>\n\n==Republican conferee meeting==\n===Candidates===\n====Nominee====\n*[[Fred Keller (politician)|Fred Keller]], state representative<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web |url=https://www.citizensvoice.com/news/list-grows-for-those-seeking-marino-seat-1.2436841 |title=List grows for those seeking Marino seat |last=Krawczeniuk |first=Borys |website=citizensvoice.com |date=January 25, 2019 |access-date=March 7, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.centredaily.com/latest-news/article227023819.html |title=GOP state lawmaker becomes favorite in House race to succeed Marino |date=March 2, 2019 |last=Levy |first=Marc |newspaper=Center Daily Times |agency=Associated Press |access-date=March 7, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n====Defeated at the convention====\n*Jessica Bowman-Hosley, professor<ref name=\"CVlist\"/>\n*Malcolm Derk, former [[Snyder County, Pennsylvania|Snyder County]] commissioner<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Commissioner Malcolm Derk is running for US Congress|url=http://www.wkok.com/former-county-commissioner-malcolm-derk-is-running-for-us-congress/|publisher=WKOK|date=February 17, 2019|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n*Kevin Ferrara, veteran<ref name=\"CVlist\"/>\n*Stacy Garrity, businesswoman<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cole|first1=John|title=PA12: Stacy Garrity Announces Bid for GOP Primary|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa12-stacy-garrity-announces-bid-for-gop-primary/90347/|publisher=PoliticsPA|date=February 12, 2019|accessdate=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n*Davis C. Haire, doctor<ref name=\"CVlist\"/>\n*Chris Hoffman, vice president of the Pennsylvania Farm Bureau<ref>{{cite web|last=Dandes |first=Rick|url=https://www.dailyitem.com/election_2019/candidates-step-forward-to-replace-marino-in-u-s-congress/article_3651c20c-bac4-58bf-b331-e571b5c8a2cf.html |title=Candidates step forward to replace Marino in U.S. Congress &#124; Election 2019 |publisher=dailyitem.com |date= |accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref>\n*Matthew McDermott<ref name=\"CVlist\"/>\n*Doug McLinko, [[Br