es elections|Pennsylvania 12]]\n[[Category:Special elections to the 116th United States Congress|Pennsylvania 2019 12]]\n[[Category:2019 Pennsylvania elections|United States House of Representatives 12]]\n[[Category:United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania|2019 12]]\n[[Category:United States House of Representatives special elections|Pennsylvania 2019 12]]\n[[Category:Pennsylvania special elections|United States House of Representatives 2019 12]]\n", "text_old": "{{see also|2019 United States elections}}\n{{short description|Election to fill a U.S. House seat vacated by resignation}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = Pennsylvania's 12th congressional district special election\n| country = Pennsylvania\n| type = by-election\n| ongoing = No\n| previous_election = 2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania#District 12\n| previous_year = 2018\n| election_date = May 21, 2019\n| next_election = 2020 United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania#District 12\n| next_year = 2020\n| seats_for_election = [[Pennsylvania's 12th congressional district]]\n| image1 = [[File:Fred Keller, official portrait, 116th Congress (cropped2).jpg|x150px]]\n| nominee1 = [[Fred Keller (politician)|'''Fred Keller''']]\n| party1 = Republican Party (United States)\n| popular_vote1 = '''90,000'''\n| percentage1 = '''68.08%'''\n| map_image = File:2019 Pennsylvania's 12th congressional district special election - Results by county.svg\n| map_size = 270px\n| map_caption = \n| image2 = [[File:No image.svg|x120px]]\n| nominee2 = Marc Friedenberg\n| party2 = Democratic Party (United States)\n| popular_vote2 = 42,195\n| percentage2 = 31.92%\n| title = U.S. Representative\n| before_election = [[Tom Marino]]\n| before_party = Republican Party (United States)\n| after_election = [[Fred Keller (politician)|Fred Keller]]\n| after_party = Republican Party (United States)\n}}\n{{Elections in Pennsylvania}}\nA [[special election]] was held on May 21, 2019, to fill the remainder of the term for {{ushr|PA|12}} in the [[United States House of Representatives]] for the [[116th United States Congress]]. [[Tom Marino]], a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]], resigned from office effective January 23.\n\n== Background ==\nAs a result of the [[2018 United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania|2018 elections]], [[United States congressional delegations from Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania's House delegation]] to the [[116th United States Congress|116th U.S. Congress]] took office in early January 2019 with a tie of 9 [[Republican Party (United States)|Republicans]] and 9 [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Levy |first=Marc |title=Democrats, 4 of them women, win House seats in Pennsylvania |url=https://www.apnews.com/058759f2b3c548d7884299fbbf357bf7 |agency=Associated Press |date=November 6, 2018 |accessdate=February 27, 2019}}</ref>\n\nRepublican [[Tom Marino]], the [[incumbent]] representative for {{ushr|PA|12}}, announced his resignation effective January 23, 2019. By state law, [[Governor of Pennsylvania|Governor]] [[Tom Wolf]] was required to call for a special election at least 60 days after the seat became vacant.<ref>{{cite web|first1=Caitlin|last1=Oprysko|first2=Zach|last2=Motellaro |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2019/01/17/tom-marino-retire-1109470 |title=Pennsylvania GOP Rep. Tom Marino to retire this month |publisher=Politico |date=January 17, 2019 |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> Wolf set the election for May 21.<ref>{{cite tweet|author=[[Tom Wolf]]|user=GovernorTomWolf|number=1088421289008738304|date=January 24, 2019|title=Having heard the concerns of county officials, I am scheduling the special election to fill the remainder of Congressman Marino\u2019s term on May 21, 2019 to coincide with the primary election.|accessdate=January 24, 2019}}</ref> Primary elections were not held in the race. Instead, nominees were chosen by each party.<ref>{{cite web|last=Paez |first=Sarah |url=https://www.centredaily.com/news/local/article224682630.html |title=Congressman Tom Marino resigns, leaving vacancy in Pa.\u2019s 12th district &#124; Centre Daily Times |publisher=Centredaily.com |date= |accessdate=January 17, 2019}}</ref> Republicans selected their nominee on March 2.<ref name=\"CVlist\"/>\n\n==Republican conferee meeting==\n===Candidates===\n====Nominee====\n*[[Fred Keller (politician)|Fred Keller]], state representative<ref name=\":8\">{{cite web |url=https://www.citizensvoice.com/news/list-grows-for-those-seeking-marino-seat-1.2436841 |title=List grows for those seeking Marino seat |last=Krawczeniuk |first=Borys |website=citizensvoice.com |date=January 25, 2019 |access-date=March 7, 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.centredaily.com/latest-news/article227023819.html |title=GOP state lawmaker becomes favorite in House race to succeed Marino |date=March 2, 2019 |last=Levy |first=Marc |newspaper=Center Daily Times |agency=Associated Press |access-date=March 7, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n====Defeated at the convention====\n*Jessica Bowman-Hosley, professor<ref name=\"CVlist\"/>\n*Malcolm Derk, former [[Snyder County, Pennsylvania|Snyder County]] commissioner<ref>{{cite news|title=Former Commissioner Malcolm Derk is running for US Congress|url=http://www.wkok.com/former-county-commissioner-malcolm-derk-is-running-for-us-congress/|publisher=WKOK|date=February 17, 2019|accessdate=February 18, 2019}}</ref>\n*Kevin Ferrara, veteran<ref name=\"CVlist\"/>\n*Stacy Garrity, businesswoman<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cole|first1=John|title=PA12: Stacy Garrity Announces Bid for GOP Primary|url=http://www.politicspa.com/pa12-stacy-garrity-announces-bid-for-gop-primary/90347/|publisher=PoliticsPA|date=February 12, 2019|accessdate=February 13, 2019}}</ref>\n*Davis C. Haire, doctor<ref name=\"CVlist\"/>\n*Chris Hoffman, vice president of the Pennsylvania Farm Bureau<ref>{{cite web